  <main>
    <section class="hero">
      <div class="hero-inner">
        <span class="eyebrow">Naloxone saves lives</span>
        <h2>Recognize an overdose. Act fast. Keep our campus safe.</h2>
        <p>
          This student‑built guide shows you how to spot the signs of an opioid overdose and use
          <strong>Narcan® (naloxone) 4 mg nasal spray</strong>. It also lists on‑campus options to get naloxone and training.
        </p>
        <div class="cta-row">
          <a class="btn primary" href="#use">How to use Narcan</a>
          <a class="btn outline" href="#where">Find naloxone near UT</a>
        </div>
        <p class="note" style="margin-top:12px">In an emergency, call <strong>911</strong> immediately.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="recognize" class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Recognize the signs of an opioid overdose</h2>
      <p class="sub">If you suspect an overdose, call 911. Then follow the steps below.</p>
      <div class="cards">
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>Common signs</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Unresponsive, can’t be woken up</li>
            <li>Slow, shallow, or no breathing; gurgling/snoring sounds</li>
            <li>Pale, clammy skin; blue or gray lips/fingertips</li>
            <li>Pinpoint pupils</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>What to do first</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Call <strong>911</strong> and state “possible opioid overdose”</li>
            <li>Lay the person on their back and clear the airway</li>
            <li>Be ready to start rescue breathing if needed</li>
            <li>Give naloxone as soon as it’s available</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="use" class="wrap">
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div>
          <h2 class="section-title">How to use Narcan® nasal spray (4 mg)</h2>
          <p class="sub">One device = one dose. If there’s no response in 2–3 minutes, give another dose with a new device.</p>
          <div class="steps">
            <div class="step"><div class="badge" aria-hidden="true"></div><div><strong>Call 911</strong>. If available, ask someone nearby to grab naloxone and an AED.</div></div>
            <div class="step"><div class="badge" aria-hidden="true"></div><div><strong>Lay on back, tilt head</strong>. Support the neck. Insert tip into a nostril until your fingers touch the nose.</div></div>
            <div class="step"><div class="badge" aria-hidden="true"></div><div><strong>Press plunger firmly</strong> to release the dose. Remove the device after spraying.</div></div>
            <div class="step"><div class="badge" aria-hidden="true"></div><div><strong>Start rescue breathing</strong> if not breathing normally: 1 breath every 5–6 seconds. If trained and needed, begin CPR.</div></div>
            <div class="step"><div class="badge" aria-hidden="true"></div><div><strong>Repeat in 2–3 minutes</strong> with a new device if there’s little/no response or if breathing slows again.</div></div>
            <div class="step"><div class="badge" aria-hidden="true"></div><div><strong>Stay with the person</strong> until help arrives. Place in the recovery position if they start breathing on their own.</div></div>
          </div>
          <p class="note" style="margin-top:10px">Naloxone has a short effect. Symptoms can return—monitor closely and be ready to give another dose.</p>
        </div>
        <aside class="card" aria-label="Important safety notes">
          <span class="pill" aria-hidden="true">Important</span>
          <ul>
            <li>Naloxone will not harm someone if opioids are not present.</li>
            <li>Store at room temperature; check expiration dates.</li>
            <li>Good‑Samaritan protections vary by state; know your local policy.</li>
          </ul>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="where" class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Where to get naloxone near UT Austin</h2>
      <p class="sub">Availability changes—call or check the linked pages to confirm. Many Texas pharmacies can dispense naloxone without an individual prescription under a standing order.</p>
      <div class="cards">
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>On‑campus & UT‑affiliated</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>University Health Services (UHS) — ask about naloxone access & brief education.</li>
            <li><a href="https://shift.utexas.edu/operation-naloxone.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Operation Naloxone (UT College of Pharmacy)</a> — awareness, trainings, and where to access free Narcan on/near campus.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>Community options</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.austintexas.gov/department/preventing-opioid-overdose" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City of Austin: Preventing Opioid Overdose</a> — local guidance and resources.</li>
            <li>Nearby pharmacies (chains & independents around campus corridors). Call to confirm stock & insurance coverage.</li>
            <li>Harm‑reduction organizations with free kits at select events (see Training section for local partners).</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
      <p class="note">If you have naloxone, keep it accessible, check expiration dates, and consider carrying two doses.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="training" class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Training & preparedness</h2>
      <div class="cards">
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>Get trained</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.traviscountytx.gov/news/2025/2787-free-narcan-use-training" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Travis County: Free Narcan® use training</a> — periodic community trainings.</li>
            <li><a href="https://txoti.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Texas Overdose Naloxone Initiative (TONI)</a> — “Breathe Now” training & curriculum.</li>
            <li><a href="https://shift.utexas.edu/operation-naloxone.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Operation Naloxone (UT)</a> — campus‑focused education and distribution info.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>Build a kit</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>2× Narcan® 4 mg devices</li>
            <li>Face shield for rescue breathing</li>
            <li>Nitrile gloves; pocket card with quick steps</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="faq" class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Can naloxone be used on someone who isn’t overdosing on opioids?</summary>
        <p>Yes. Naloxone targets opioid receptors and won’t harm someone if opioids aren’t involved.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How long does naloxone last?</summary>
        <p>Its effects can wear off in 30–90 minutes. Breathing may slow again—monitor and repeat doses as needed.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What should I expect after giving naloxone?</summary>
        <p>The person may wake up disoriented or in withdrawal. Keep them safe, explain what happened, and wait for EMS.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

    <section id="resources" class="wrap">
      <h2 class="section-title">Evidence & resources</h2>
      <div class="cards">
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>Why this matters for UT students</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>About <strong>1 in 5</strong> students reported lifetime nonmedical use of at least one prescription medication class in a large multi‑campus study. [Addictive Behaviors, 2004, DOI link below]</li>
            <li>Many students’ <strong>first opportunities</strong> to try prescription opioids occur <strong>after matriculation</strong>, highlighting college as a key window for initial exposure. [Journal link below]</li>
            <li>Family‑focused prevention (ISFP) in adolescence showed a <strong>65% relative reduction</strong> in prescription opioid misuse by age 25. [AJPH 2012, DOI link below]</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="note">These findings support campus‑level education, easy naloxone access, and evidence‑based prevention.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="card span-6">
          <h3>Local info & free trainings</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.austintexas.gov/department/preventing-opioid-overdose" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City of Austin: Preventing Opioid Overdose</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.traviscountytx.gov/news/2025/2787-free-narcan-use-training" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Travis County — Free Narcan use training</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://txoti.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Texas Overdose Naloxone Initiative (TONI)</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://shift.utexas.edu/operation-naloxone.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Operation Naloxone — UT College of Pharmacy</a></li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
      <h3 style="margin-top:18px">Referenced studies (DOIs)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/07448481.2018.1549049" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Opioid overdose in university settings (Journal of American College Health, 2018)</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.addbeh.2004.08.024" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Prevalence of nonmedical use among college students (Addictive Behaviors, 2004)</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.addbeh.2014.03.008" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Trends in prescription medication misuse in college (Addictive Behaviors, 2014)</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/08897070802418451" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Contexts & initiation of prescription opioid misuse in college (Substance Use & Misuse, 2009)</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://doi.org/10.2105/AJPH.2012.301209" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Effect of ISFP on later prescription drug misuse (American Journal of Public Health, 2012)</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
